This is, in fact, the Ukrainian Greco-Catholic Cathedral of St. Volodymyr the Great. It is the cathedral of the Ukrainian Greco-Catholic Eparchy of France, Benelux and Switzerland, shepherded until 2019 by Bishop Borys (Gudziak), who is now the Metropolitan Archbishop of Philadelphia for the Ukrainian Greco-Catholic Church in the United States.

It is the cathedral of the Ukrainian Greek Catholic Church. Classicist architectural style, but with a striking iconostasis. Some icons are so special that they are sure to make a splash on your Instagram. I've seen all 15 seasons of Supernatural, but even watching this horror series didn't scare me as much as seeing this iconostasis. I'm just using two photos here as examples. Those responsible are 100% fans of horror films, because the beautiful icons are pushed to the sidelines (see photo), but the ones from the iconostasis catch the eye. Regarding prayer times: On weekdays the Divine Liturgy is at 6 p.m., followed by Vespers. On Saturday at 9 a.m. the divine. Liturgy for the deceased, at 5 p.m. the great vespers and at 6 p.m. another divine one. Liturgy. On Sunday the liturgies take place 8 a.m., 10 a.m., 12 p.m. and 5 p.m.

The Ukrainian Greek-Catholic Cathedral of St. Volodymyr the Great operates in the center of Paris on Boulevard Saint-Germain. A cozy, friendly, authentic Ukrainian church in the heart of Paris! To the left of the iconostasis is a commemorative plaque with photos of the Heroes of the Heavenly Hundred... The history of St. Volodymyr's Church is connected with the name of Simon Petliura. Near the entrance there are two memorial tables, in Ukrainian and French, which announce that the Chief Otaman of the Ukrainian People's Republic died here after being mortally wounded... 50 years ago, a square named after Taras Shevchenko was built around the church and a bust of the poet by M. Lysenko was installed. I had the good fortune to attend the evening service in this church on the Day of the Ukrainian Slut. Thank you very much!
